# 2026-03-03 (cont. 6 — decoder refactor: separation of concerns)

Refactored Decoder.cs to clean up responsibility boundaries, naming, and conventions.

## What Was Built

* Decoder.cs — pulled direction (D bit) logic out of `ParseModRMByte`. Method now returns `(reg, rm)` tuple; `Decode` assigns source/destination via ternary based on D bit. Eliminated duplicated if/else swap block.
* Decoder.cs — `ParseModRMByte` collapsed to 3 lines: extract, offset, return. No intermediate nullable variables.
* Decoder.cs — renamed `_byteOneLookAhead` → `_hasModRM`. Says what it means.
* Decoder.cs — all local variables fixed to camelCase (`direction`, `word`, `operation`, `source`, `destination`, `offset`).
* Decoder.cs — `parseModRMByte` → `ParseModRMByte` (PascalCase method).
* Opcode00Tests.cs — unskipped integration test, added test name to failure messages (prior session, captured here).
* TestModel.cs — added `ToString() => Name` on TestCase (prior session, captured here).
* docs/refactor-todo.md — created refactor tracking doc.

## Key Decisions

+ Direction swap belongs in `Decode`, not `ParseModRMByte`. The ModR/M byte resolves operands (reg, rm); the D bit decides which is source vs destination. Clean separation of concerns.
+ `ParseModRMByte` returns structurally named tuple `(reg, rm)` not semantically named `(Source, Destination)` — it doesn't know about roles, only about fields.
+ Ternary pair `source = !direction ? reg : rm` / `destination = direction ? reg : rm` — flips operand assignment, not operand order. No duplication.

## Resolved

+ Direction responsibility — lives in `Decode`, not in ModR/M parsing.
+ Naming conventions — all locals camelCase, methods PascalCase, private static field `_hasModRM` descriptive.
+ Prior session commits (4a37f06, e3ce9e4) now documented in .plan.

## Open

? `Decode_0x03` test passes `[0x03]` (1 byte) but 0x03 needs a ModR/M byte — will break when registered in `_hasModRM`.
? `[Theory]`/`[MemberData]` for Opcode00Tests — monolithic 10k loop has no per-case discovery.
? Memory and immediate operand representation on DecodedInstruction still TBD.

